WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:08.000
So when do you want to use a custom hook instead of just creating another component?

00:08.000 --> 00:16.000
Yeah, it's a good question. My first answer to your question is there are divided opinions on the matter.

00:16.000 --> 00:25.000
So there's not a right answer here. The extreme side of one of it is there are some people that I know that will say,

00:25.000 --> 00:30.000
never put an effect in your component, ever, period, end of sentence,

00:30.000 --> 00:35.000
and that any effect should always go on a custom hook.

00:35.000 --> 00:43.000
That's one side of it. There's an amount of validity to it because then the nice thing about custom hooks is they become easy to test in isolation,

00:43.000 --> 00:52.000
as opposed to like a part of a great component. You can test just that the hook is working. That can be nice, right?

00:52.000 --> 00:57.000
The other side of people's like, never write any custom hooks, always put it in the component.

00:57.000 --> 01:08.000
I think there's less validity to that. I'm probably mostly to the side of most effects should probably end up in custom hooks

01:08.000 --> 01:17.000
if they're shared at all or need to be tested, which usually one of those is true, right?

01:17.000 --> 01:27.000
Yeah. So the nice thing about this hook, during the testing section, we will actually write tests for this hook, so you'll actually see how to test hooks.

01:27.000 --> 01:34.000
We can test that it's calling the API, it's using the right parameters, it does the right thing when there's nothing there,

01:34.000 --> 01:45.000
it does the right thing when there is something there. It becomes very, very straightforward and very easy to test.

01:45.000 --> 01:50.000
And then now if I had like a, let's say I was writing like the admin dashboard for this,

01:50.000 --> 01:58.000
and I needed to fetch the pizza of the day so I could show like, you know, stats for how many pizzas of the days that we were able to push,

01:58.000 --> 02:06.000
I could just use this hook over again, right? Yeah. And this just immediately gives it back to me. I don't have to rewrite the logic again.

02:06.000 --> 02:14.000
So hopefully that kind of bounds the box of where your opinion should lie, right? Somewhere in there.

02:14.000 --> 02:21.000
In this specific case where we only are using pizza of the day in this very one place, I'm going to put in the component,

02:21.000 --> 02:32.000
because this is not an interesting enough custom hook for me to try and encapsulate it or test it to all hell and back, right?

02:32.000 --> 02:40.000
I'm sure you've all heard of dry code, right? Do not repeat yourself. I'm a wet code person.

02:40.000 --> 02:48.000
Write everything thrice. The third time I go to write, like copy a piece of logic, I'm like, okay, maybe I should put this into a module and reuse it, right?

02:48.000 --> 02:55.000
First time, absolutely not. Second time might be a fluke. Third time, it probably is like app code that I need to test.

02:55.000 --> 03:00.000
There's kind of my methodology, but up to you.

03:00.000 --> 03:07.000
Let's say that the network call takes a long time to respond. Will this cause a delay in the rendering from the custom hook,

03:07.000 --> 03:12.000
or will it return undefined first and then when it has a value, return the updated value?

03:12.000 --> 03:22.000
Good question. Let's walk through it. Pizza of the day. After we're done with this section, I'm never saying pizza of the day ever again,

03:22.000 --> 03:27.000
for the record, until we get to the testing section and then I'm right back on the pony.

03:27.000 --> 03:38.000
I have this function here, which calls this. This is not await or anything like that. This is just directly calling the function.

03:38.000 --> 03:49.000
This is not awaiting. This is sync. This is going to call this. It's going to go into here, and it's going to set this to be null, right?

03:49.000 --> 03:56.000
It's then going to schedule an effect to be run. Keep in mind, renders finish first before their effects happen.

03:56.000 --> 04:01.000
Your first render is always going to be done by the time the effect is actually run.

04:01.000 --> 04:11.000
This effect, this function here, is scheduled to run, but does not run yet. What gets returned on the first render?

04:12.000 --> 04:20.000
Null. That's the default value. This is pizza of the day for the first render before this effect has been run.

04:20.000 --> 04:32.000
This return here is going to be null, which means here is null. What happens when we hit this block with null?

04:33.000 --> 04:39.000
It's going to just return loading. It returns, right? This is an early return pattern, right?

04:39.000 --> 04:45.000
And so none of this gets run. It just returns this in short circuits here.

04:45.000 --> 04:51.000
Now the effect runs. We get back from the API. The set gets called. This gets rendered again.

04:51.000 --> 04:58.000
This is now actually an object that came back from the API. Is it null? No.

04:58.000 --> 05:01.000
So all of this is going to get rendered.

05:03.000 --> 05:12.000
So, I mean, let's just super draw this out into being agonizing. I'll wait for 10 seconds.

05:14.000 --> 05:18.000
Alright, so yeah, I got it copilot.

05:19.000 --> 05:25.000
See this very small loading down here? I am very talented with loading spinners, as you can see.

05:26.000 --> 05:29.000
But nothing is being rendered down there, and then eventually it shows up.

05:29.000 --> 05:36.000
Did you use a lowercase u in the file name of the custom hook because it's a naming convention?

05:36.000 --> 05:44.000
Yeah, so like use pizza of the day here. Yeah, let's talk about the name kind of in general.

05:44.000 --> 05:48.000
It's a lowercase u because it's not a component, right? What is this returning?

05:49.000 --> 05:54.000
This returns a hook, which is not renderable by and of itself in React.

05:54.000 --> 06:01.000
It's part of a composable part of what a component can use to get data.

06:01.000 --> 06:08.000
So maybe say that differently. Only components have the convention of being named in uppercase.

06:08.000 --> 06:12.000
And just to be super clear, the file names really don't matter.

06:12.000 --> 06:17.000
You will see people call this like pizza.jsx like this.

06:24.000 --> 06:29.000
Because like Linux file systems are insensitive and most of our stuff is always running on Linux, right?

06:29.000 --> 06:35.000
So you can run into issues actually by uppercasing things that did happen to me at Netflix one time.

06:37.000 --> 06:39.000
That usually doesn't matter. Usually don't have to care.

06:39.000 --> 06:48.000
Usually the convention of putting uppercase here is useful for me at a glance to say like this is a component and exports a component.

06:50.000 --> 06:56.000
So another way of stating this is this is not a component and anything that's not a component, I always just lowercase name.

06:56.000 --> 06:59.000
It's really only components that get the uppercase.

07:01.000 --> 07:07.000
And then we did talk about earlier that it is important for the name of the thing.

07:07.000 --> 07:14.000
So looking at order here, that pizza does need to be uppercase P for that.

07:15.000 --> 07:18.000
Now, the next thing to say is use.

07:20.000 --> 07:23.000
Hooks have use in front of it. That is a convention.

07:24.000 --> 07:29.000
It's not necessarily going to break React, but if you use use in your name,

07:29.000 --> 07:35.000
then all of the React linting will catch errors that you would do with potentially with a hook, right?

07:35.000 --> 07:39.000
So we haven't put it in here. In fact, I don't even know if I do it in here.

07:42.000 --> 07:54.000
If we go into pizza the day here and if I say like something like if true or something like that, is this going to catch this?

07:56.000 --> 07:59.000
It does. Look at that. No, never mind. It doesn't.

07:59.000 --> 08:11.000
If I had the React hooks ES lint rules in here, it would catch this because even though pizza of the day is not its own type of hook,

08:11.000 --> 08:16.000
it knows it's like this begins with use and therefore I know that this cannot be inside of an if statement.

08:19.000 --> 08:22.000
Beyond that, it's just very easy to see at a glance.

08:22.000 --> 08:28.000
Use pizza of the day, very obvious that this is a custom hook, right?

08:29.000 --> 08:36.000
So while you don't have to, as your future coworker, you do have to.

